  Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Walsingham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Donal.","English: habitational name from Great or Little Walsingham in Norfolk. The placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wæls</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i> (genitive <i>-inga-</i>) + <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard de Walsingham III was born about 1326, in Little Walsingham, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas de Walsingham, was 22 and his mother, Agnes de Stafford, was 37. He married Margaret Nortoft about 1346, in Waterden, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1365, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 40."},"et":{"ABT 1326–1365":"umbes 1326–1365","1326–1365":"1326–1365","1327–Female":"1327–Surnud","1329–Female":"1329–Surnud","1348–Male":"1348–Surnud","1351–1409":"1351–1409","1353–1409":"1353–1409","1306–1327":"1306–1327","1290–Female":"1290–Surnud","Abt 1348":"umbes 1348","1351":"1351","ABT 1326":"umbes 1326","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1348":"1348","1326":"1326","Abt 1353":"umbes 1353","1365":"1365","about 1325":"umbes 1325","1353":"1353","about 1346":"umbes 1346","1409":"1409","1329":"1329","1306":"1306","Egmere, Norfolk, England":"Waterden, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Little Walsingham, Norfolk, England":"Little Walsingham, Norfolk, England","Of, Little Walsingham, Norfolk, England":"Little Walsingham, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1326–1365":"noin 1326–1365","1326–1365":"1326–1365","1327–Female":"1327–Kuollut","1329–Female":"1329–Kuollut","1348–Male":"1348–Kuollut","1351–1409":"1351–1409","1353–1409":"1353–1409","1306–1327":"1306–1327","1290–Female":"1290–Kuollut","Abt 1348":"noin 1348","1351":"1351","ABT 1326":"noin 1326","1290":"1290","1327":"1327","1348":"1348","1326":"1326","Abt 1353":"noin 1353","1365":"1365